#2. Understanding CRUD Operations 
print("UNDERSTANDING CRUD OPERATIONS")

crud_operations = """ 
CRUD = Create, Read, Update, Delete

 1.CREATE (INSERT)
   Purpose: Add new data to database
   SQL: INSERT INTO table (column1, column2) VALUES (?, ?)
   Python: cursor.execute(insert_query, data)
   
   Example: Add a new campaign to campaigns table
   ✅ Use when: Creating new records (new campaign, new manager, etc.)
   ❌ Avoid when: Modifying existing records (use UPDATE instead)
   
2. READ (SELECT)
   Purpose: Retrieve data from database
   SQL: SELECT * FROM table WHERE condition
   Python: cursor.execute(select_query)
         results = cursor.fetchall()  OR  pd.read_sql_query()
   
   Example: Get all campaigns by a specific manager
   ✅ Use when: Querying, analyzing, displaying data
   ❌ Avoid when: Modifying data (use INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE instead)
   
3. UPDATE
   Purpose: Modify existing data in database
   SQL: UPDATE table SET column1 = ? WHERE condition
   Python: cursor.execute(update_query, data)
   
   Example: Update the budget of a specific campaign
   ✅ Use when: Modifying existing records
   ❌ Avoid when: Creating new records (use INSERT instead)
   
4. DELETE
   Purpose: Remove data from database
   SQL: DELETE FROM table WHERE condition
   Python: cursor.execute(delete_query, data)
   
   Example: Delete a specific campaign
   ✅ Use when: Removing records
   ❌ Avoid when: Querying or analyzing data (use SELECT instead)

   
   TRANSACTION MANAGEMENT:
- conn.commit() → Save all changes permanently
- conn.rollback() → Undo changes if something goes wrong
- Used together to ensure all-or-nothing operations
"""

print (crud_operations)

